    "en": {
      "title": "Sri Lanka coal deal awarded on 6-month credit amid queries",
      "author": "",
      "body_lines": [
        "ECONOMYNEXT \u2013 Sri Lanka has awarded a deal to supply coal to Ceylon Electricity Board on a 6-month credit facility Energy Minister Kanchana Wijesekera said amid opposition queries.",
        "The tender was awarded to the lowest bidder, Minister Wijesekera said.",
        "\u201cDue procurement process followed with evaluation & approval from STEC, SSCAPC. Supplier will provide 6 months credit facility from the date of supply of each shipment,\u201d he said in a twitter.com message.",
        "Opposition legislator Harsha de Silva queried why are two year deal was awarded to a company that was not originally shortlisted.",
        "Was #SriLanka\u2019s LARGEST EVER PROCUREMENT amounting to USD 1,477 million to purchase 4.5m MT of coal on a 2 year term deal AWARDED today to a company that was NOT even SHORTLISTED by the tender committee? Can @TimesOnlineLK who y\u2019day made the allegation this could happen, confirm? pic.twitter.com/BRPekGRivd",
        "Global coal and oil prices are at high levels in 2021 amid the so-called Powell Bubble fired by the US Federal Reserve.",
        "The Fed however is tightening monetary policy and the US dollar is already strengthening. Commodity prices are expected to edge down as monetary tightening takes effect.",
        "Sri Lanka has a 900MW coal plant which supplies over 30 percent of the energy needs. (Colombo/Aug27/2022)"
      ],
